 class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-36-calculating-horizontal-ruffles-for-the-face-of-the-skirt/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-36-calculating-horizontal-ruffles-for-the-face-of-the-skirt/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:37:49+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T18:37:49+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 36. Calculating Horizontal Ruffles for the Face of the Skirt."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 36. Calculating Horizontal Ruffles for the Face of the Skirt."><meta itemprop="description" content="You are talking with a client and get lost when it comes to discussing the budget? The bride shows you a picture of a skirt generously covered by ruffles or flounces"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 36. Calculating Horizontal Ruffles for the Face of the Skirt.</h1><p><strong>This tutorial will be devoted to face skirts with ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>Isn’t it a familiar situation: </strong>you are talking with a client and get lost when it comes to discussing the budget? The bride shows you a picture of a skirt generously covered by ruffles or flounces and you just can’t imagine how many meters of fabric and hours of work it will take to sew a garment like this. At such moments, you really wish you had a tool which could quickly calculate all ruffle lengths and fabric consumption right then and there. And knowing the total sewing edge length of all ruffles, you could estimate how much time approximately you would need to invest in the making and how much it would cost.</p><p><strong>Well! Now you have a tool like this! </strong></p><p><strong>Let us, for example, suppose that we need to calculate fabric consumption and approximate cost of production for a skirt like this: </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image001.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>First of all, let us examine the skirt and try to “extract” as much information as possible from this picture. </strong></p><p><strong>I have calculated eleven ruffles on this skirt. And I think its bottom circumference is about 3m. </strong></p><p><strong>Open the Table for Calculating a Skirt Based on Hem Length. </strong></p><p><strong>Here is the plan: </strong>we will first determine the sector angle for cutting this skirt, then divide the skirt in gores, and then do calculations for the horizontal ruffles.</p><p><strong>Go to the Skirt tab of the table.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image007.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I put the supposed initial parameters under Key Skirt Parameters (red arrows): </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 75cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 110cm,</p><p>- Back Skirt Length – 110cm since there is no train.</p><p>- Hem Length – 300cm,</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>The table offers the following calculated parameters: </strong></p><p>- HC max – 112cm. Let us consider that our client’s hip circumference should be smaller than 112cm if her waist circumference is 75cm.</p><p>- Desired Sector Angle – 117 degrees.</p><p><strong>Open the Horizontal Ruffles tab and fill in the necessary parameters: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image009.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p>- Number of Skirt Ruffles (Train Excluded) – 11 (as seen on the picture);</p><p>- Ruffles Overlap – say, 3cm,</p><p>- Looking at the picture, I suggest we use a gathering ratio of 10 for our ruffles. You can see that these ruffles are made of very thickly gathered soft tulle. I would, however, recommend that you test your ruffle fabric in each particular case before cutting them.</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 300cm. Let us consider that we are going to cut the ruffles from plain tulle with a width of 3m.</p><p><strong>And we get instant results: </strong></p><p>- Intervals between Ruffles – 9.7cm,</p><p>- Ruffle Strip Width (Seam Allowances Included) – 15.1cm. It is the length of the strip of fabric used for the ruffle (about 15cm).</p><p>- Finished Ruffle Width – 12.7cm (about 13cm).</p><p><strong>If we look at the right part of the table, we will see a finished pattern for cutting our skirt: </strong></p><p>- Fabric Consumption for All Ruffles – 9.7m,</p><p>- Total Sewing Edge Length of All Ruffles – 19.2m,</p><p>- And all parameters for each separate ruffle (initial length with regard to gathering ratio, sewing edge length, and distance to waistline).</p><p><strong>It has taken us just one minute to calculate fabric consumption for the ruffles of our skirt with fabric width of 3m. </strong>And now we can safely tell our client that we will need 10m of fabric with a width of 3m alone for the ruffles of her skirt. That is, without counting the fabric required for the petticoat, the skirt, and the lining. And you will need twice as much if you plan to replace soft tulle with some narrower fabric (such as soft organza with a width of 150cm) keeping the same gathering ratio. In that case, you can tell your client that you are going to need 20m of 150cm-wide fabric.</p><p><strong>Let me give you some more examples of using our automatic calculation table. </strong></p><p><strong>You can calculate fabric consumption for ruffles put only on the train of the skirt in a matter of seconds. </strong>Look at this extravagant and beautiful skirt:</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image011.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Calculated ruffle lengths will not only help you determine main fabric consumption, but also consumption of separate materials for finishing the ruffles. </strong>Knowing the total length of all ruffles and the length of each separate ruffle, you will know how much lace, decorative trimming, or other similar expensive material to buy in order to finish them.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image013.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>My tables can also be used to calculate ruffles for really full skirts: for example, full-circle skirts. </strong>Of course, full-circle skirts seldom have ruffles going along their full length, but you might want to calculate several rows of ruffles down the bottom. Such skirts look very elegant.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image015.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>You can also calculate the same parameters for a ¾ circle skirt. </strong>Just put 270 or 240 degrees in the table and not 360 degrees like for the full-circle skirt.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image017.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Please look at the skirt in the picture below. </strong>It raised lots of questions on our online forum, the key one being: how much fabric you need for a skirt like this? Only the automatic calculation table knows the answer.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image019.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We will discuss how to calculate ruffles of varied widths positioned at unequal intervals in a separate tutorial. </strong></p><p><strong>And now let me show you how to use my table to calculate vertical ruffles or flounces, for example, for a half-circle skirt with a train. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image021.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>What we see here is a fishtail skirt with the bottom part cut as a half-circle with a train prolongation. It is quite popular. </strong>The bottom part does not necessarily have to be cut as a half-circle. You will be able to shape it in different ways after getting experienced enough in working with automatic calculation tables.</p><p><strong>And now let us, for example, imagine that the base of our skirt is a half-circle with a train prolongation. </strong>We will first do all calculations for the petticoat and for its fabric casing and then talk about the face skirt.</p><p><strong>Calculations for the petticoat will be done in the Table for Calculating a Skirt Based on Hem Length with Fixed Parameters. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image023.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The first thing we need to do is decide on the initial parameters for putting in the table. </strong></p><p>Of course, the best way to determine the hem length would be to sew a mock-up petticoat. But I won’t do it now, for the sake of sparing time. I will simply assume that <strong>a petticoat with a 250cm-long bottom hoop is enough for a skirt like this. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us suppose that the flared part of the skirt is 70cm long at the front. </strong>We will not calculate any train for the petticoat because the skirt will have the same length from all sides (i.e. 70cm).</p><p><strong>Suppose the straight part of the skirt from the waist to the beginning of the flare is 40cm long. </strong></p><p><strong>In this case, the finished petticoat will have a standard length of 110cm, </strong>which is quite normal for a tall woman.</p><p><strong>Open the Skirt tab and fill in the following initial parameters to determine the sector angle: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – let it be 95cm. In this particular case, it is the circumference of the skirt at the level where the flare begins.</p><p>- Skirt Length – 70cm,</p><p>- Hem Length – 250cm,</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>As the result:</strong></p><p>- Sector Angle – 127 degrees.</p><p><strong>If you want to, </strong>you can cut the petticoat using the radii suggested by the table and the found sector angle as shown on the diagram, or divide it in gores and sew a trapeze-shaped skirt with a gore.</p><p><strong>Suppose we want to divide our petticoat in gores. </strong></p><p><strong>Open the Gores tab. </strong></p><p><strong>We are working with a table for a skirt with fixed parameters, i.e. the key skirt parameters are transferred automatically. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image025.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>All we need to do is select the desired number of gores: for example, five. </strong></p><p>The table has distributed them the following way:</p><p>- Number of Front Gores – 2,</p><p>- Number of Back Gores – 3.</p><p><strong>Besides, we get a full pattern which can be used to start cutting the garment.</strong></p><p><strong>Next we open the Horizontal Ruffles tab and calculate the lengths and positions of all tunnels for inserting steel petticoat hoops, which is something we did in the previous tutorials. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2036.files/image027.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Let us move to the fabric casing of our petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>Fabric casings for skirts like this are often cut as a half-circle </strong>unless you and your client opt for a base of some other style for putting face ruffles on it. If you notice that the bottom of the face skirt looks too full when put over a half-circle petticoat and does not answer your expectations, then you should calculate it based on the sector angle but make it looser than the petticoat. And when you start calculating the face part of the skirt, you should also increase the sector angle in order to make the top part looser than on the fabric casing.</p><p><strong>I recommend </strong>that you either sew a mock-up before sewing a full-size skirt or sew the skirt step by step: first calculate and sew the petticoat, put it on the dress-form, and measure it. And then do calculations for the fabric casing, sew it, put it on the petticoat on the dress-form, and take measurements off the resulting construction to understand what size the face skirt must be. And then you will use the table to calculate the parameters of the face skirt and the vertical ruffles.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></st